Class SoundEvent

java.lang.Object
  java.util.EventObject
      giantmetalbowserSound.SoundEvent
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable
public class SoundEvent
extends java.util.EventObject

Represents an event when a Playable starts playing, is stopped, finishes playing, or ends.

  • SOUND_PLAYED events occur when a Playable begins to play.
  • SOUND_INTERRUPTED events occur when a Playable is interrupted using its stop() method.
  • SOUND_COMPLETED events occur when a Playable reaches the end of its audio file. The Playable may or may not continue to play, depending on if it is set to repeat or not.
    • SOUND_ENDED events occur when a Playable ends
  • its playback for any reason. This can occur either by stop() method (in which case a SOUND_ENDED event is also created) or by reaching the end of the audio file (in which case a SOUND_COMPLETED events is also created).

Field Detail

SOUND_PLAYED

public static final int SOUND_PLAYED
Indicates a SoundEvent for starting playback. SOUND_PLAYED events occur either when a Playable's play() method is called, or after the Playable finished playback and is set to repeat. If a SOUND_PLAYED event is created because of repeating, it will occur after a SOUND_COMPLETED event.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

SOUND_INTERRUPTED

public static final int SOUND_INTERRUPTED
Indicates a SoundEvent for interrupting playback with stop(). A SOUND_INTERRUPTED event will be followed by a SOUND_ENDED event.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

SOUND_COMPLETED

public static final int SOUND_COMPLETED
Indicates a SoundEvent for reaching the end of the playback. If the Playable is set to repeat, the SOUND_COMPLETED event will be followed by a SOUND_PLAYED event. Otherwise, a SOUND_COMPLETED event will be followed by a SOUND_ENDED event.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

SOUND_ENDED

public static final int SOUND_ENDED
Indicates a SoundEvent for ending playback in some way, either by the stop() method or by reaching the end of playback without repeating. SOUND_ENDED events will occur after SOUND_COMPLETED or SOUND_INTERRUPTED events.

See Also:
